have amazing product managers at Figma. I've 
had three of them on the podcast already. I'm  

194
00:16:56,480 --> 00:17:01,760
curious just what value you find the 
best product managers bring to Figma?

195
00:17:01,760 --> 00:17:08,080
It was really funny last year after that 
interview, so Yuhki, our chief product officer,  

196
00:17:08,080 --> 00:17:15,600
had invited me to a dinner for our PM team. And 
it took a while to get out of Config at the end  

197
00:17:15,600 --> 00:17:25,320
of the day, and I eventually made the dinner but I 
was 40 minutes late. And I walk in and Mihika who  

198
00:17:25,320 --> 00:17:39,880
was on stage yesterday, presenting Figma Slides, 
Flides, she was standing up and doing a mock Brian  

199
00:17:39,880 --> 00:17:45,800
Chesky impersonation. And she's standing up in 
front of the entire product team and she goes,  

200
00:17:45,800 --> 00:17:52,720
"And then Brian Chesky's like, 'There don't need 
to be any PMs.' And Dylan's like... Ooh." And  

201
00:17:52,720 --> 00:18:03,320
I'm like, "Hi, Mihika." And I'd never seen her 
so red. And then I gave a quick, "Hey PM team,  

202
00:18:03,320 --> 00:18:13,120
I believe in you. Thank you for your hard work."
Seriously, I think that if you zoom out, it's  

203
00:18:13,120 --> 00:18:19,440
always tricky whenever you're asked to formally 
define, what is the separation between a product  

204
00:18:19,440 --> 00:18:25,840
manager, a designer, and an engineer? It's always 
hard to actually create those clear lines. And  

205
00:18:25,840 --> 00:18:32,280
I think in many organizations they're blurry. 
But at the end of the day, a PM and designer,  

206
00:18:32,280 --> 00:18:37,640
they need to have some technical expertise or at 
least understand how some systems work to probably  

207
00:18:37,640 --> 00:18:44,000
create the best things they can possibly make. A 
designer, engineer, they should probably have some  

208
00:18:44,000 --> 00:18:49,880
sense of the business objectives. They should 
have some sense of what users want. An engineer  

209
00:18:49,880 --> 00:18:59,920
and a product manager, they should have taste and 
craft and some sense of the option space, and some  

210
00:19:02,400 --> 00:19:10,400
desire to care about the visual implementation.
And I think you can include research in there too,  

211
00:19:10,400 --> 00:19:15,360
if you want to make it four legs of the stool 
rather than the trio. And you can talk about  

212
00:19:15,360 --> 00:19:21,800
all three probably should have exposure to users 
and be talking in dialogue with users. So I think  

213
00:19:21,800 --> 00:19:31,760
that if you think about that group holistically, 
each is important. If you think about a team,  

214
00:19:31,760 --> 00:19:36,960
there's all these qualities that you have to 
have to make a great product. And that said,  

215
00:19:36,960 --> 00:19:43,680
I think for product managers and the product 
function... I think sometimes when you see people  

216
00:19:43,680 --> 00:19:49,160
that fall down in that function is because 
they treat it too much like process. Which  

217
00:19:49,160 --> 00:19:59,040
is very important too, don't me wrong. Good 
process can help support good outcomes. But  

218
00:19:59,040 --> 00:20:03,760
I think that you can't lose sight of the problems 
that you're solving. You have to go talk to users  

219
00:20:03,760 --> 00:20:07,880
and you have to actually have a strategy. And 
if you're really good, you should have a point  

220
00:20:07,880 --> 00:20:12,160
of view. And some point of views are going to 
lead to good outcomes and some point of views  

221
00:20:12,160 --> 00:20:20,000
aren't. And there's some tense sense of taste.
And you also have to bring everyone together  

222
00:20:20,000 --> 00:20:26,120
and make sure that they get to the objective, 
that it's celebrated, and that at the end of  

223
00:20:26,120 --> 00:20:32,000
the project or when you complete a milestone, 
everyone's stoked. Otherwise, it's not going to  

224
00:20:32,000 --> 00:20:37,680
be a team that gels, you're not going to get to 
the next outcome. Even if you get to an outcome  

225
00:20:37,680 --> 00:20:44,440
and it's a milestone, but if everyone's unhappy, 
you failed. And so somehow good product people are  

226
00:20:44,440 --> 00:20:48,600
able to do all this and they're able to create 
great frameworks that bring everyone along with  

227
00:20:48,600 --> 00:20:54,840
them. And so everyone's able to have a shared head 
space around what it is they're trying to get to.

228
00:20:54,840 --> 00:21:02,440
Someone once said that if PMs disappeared or if a 
PM goes on vacation, everything's okay for a week  

229
00:21:02,440 --> 00:21:07,960
or two or three and then things start to crumble a 
little bit because they glue everything together.  

230
00:21:08,680 --> 00:21:12,720
Do you find that sort of thing? Let me actually 
ask a different question along those lines,  

231
00:21:12,720 --> 00:21:18,360
are you bearish or bullish on the future of 
product management? Do you think PMs will continue  

232
00:21:18,360 --> 00:21:23,280
the way they are? Do you think PMs will dwindle 
any sense of the future of product management?

233
00:21:24,000 --> 00:21:30,360
I think probably everyone's learning to do a 
bit more of everyone else's job in this current  

234
00:21:30,360 --> 00:21:37,560
moment. That said, I definitely think there's 
still immense value in product, immense value  

235
00:21:37,560 --> 00:21:43,240
in design, immense value in engineering. And 
so I think those roles will continue to exist.

236
00:21:43,240 --> 00:21:49,480
So maybe I just want to come back to the question 
of just, with the best PMs that you work with,  

237
00:21:49,480 --> 00:21:53,800
do you find, what value do they most bring? 
I guess is there anything that's like,  

238
00:21:53,800 --> 00:21:57,520
"Here's what would be gone 
if we didn't have these PMs"?

239
00:21:57,520 --> 00:22:03,520
The best PMs, I think again, create those 
frameworks that bring everyone else along  

240
00:22:03,520 --> 00:22:07,360
and those frameworks also have a point of 
view and a strategy associated with them.  

241
00:22:07,360 --> 00:22:12,560
So you're able to take the strategy, take the 
point of view, wrap it all up in a framework,  

242
00:22:12,560 --> 00:22:18,920
and then make it so that everyone knows what 
the destination is and how to get there.

243
00:22:20,360 --> 00:22:25,880
So along these lines, something I've heard you're 
really big on is simplification. Somebody told  

244
00:22:25,880 --> 00:22:30,840
me that when you're in a designer view and 
things just feel too complex to you, quote,  

245
00:22:30,840 --> 00:22:37,160
"You furrow your brow and insist there must be 
something simpler." Why is simplification so  

246
00:22:37,160 --> 00:22:41,360
top of mind for you, why is it so important 
for you and just why is it so hard to do?

247
00:22:41,360 --> 00:22:48,800
Oh, gosh. Well, I think probably anyone here 
who's worked on product knows how hard it is. I  

248
00:22:48,800 --> 00:22:58,640
think the more that you add, the harder it is to 
create something that's coherent. One essay that  

249
00:22:58,640 --> 00:23:05,240
Evan, my co-founder, introduced me to early 
on in famous history, I think from Stevie's  

250
00:23:05,240 --> 00:23:10,760
[inaudible 00:23:06] grants or something like 
that, contains the term irreducible complexity.  

251
00:23:10,760 --> 00:23:15,080
And it's basically this idea that one plus one 
does not equal three, it sometimes equals one  

252
00:23:15,080 --> 00:23:21,760
and a half. And the more that you add and the 
more that you continue to put in something,  

253
00:23:21,760 --> 00:23:28,040
the more complex it gets and the worse it gets. 
And I think this is definitely true for tools. 

254
00:23:28,040 --> 00:23:33,400
So in the context of Figma, we can make 
it more powerful, but to do that in a way  

255
00:23:33,400 --> 00:23:40,480
that's not making it more complex at the same 
time is extremely hard. And we have to always  

256
00:23:40,480 --> 00:23:48,720
be paying attention to how complex or how simple 
things are because if we don't, it just becomes a  

257
00:23:48,720 --> 00:23:53,440
monstrosity really fast. And there's parts of our 
product that, I don't want to dive into that part  

258
00:23:53,440 --> 00:23:58,840
of the conversation, the self-critique, 
but definitely as I'm in conversation  

259
00:23:58,840 --> 00:24:02,000
with a bunch of our product leaders at 
Figma, there's parts where it's like, "Okay,  

260
00:24:02,000 --> 00:24:08,600
this thing is too complex as a system and we made 
all the right local decisions and yet together  

261
00:24:08,600 --> 00:24:14,120
they're too complex and they're not working 
anymore. And let's go revisit the system now."

