270
00:24:59,200 --> 00:25:02,720
I know you just redesigned Figma. I imagine part 
of that came from things are just getting too  

271
00:25:02,720 --> 00:25:06,720
complicated, not as simple as we want. Is there 
anything that's been bugging you in the old Figma  

272
00:25:06,720 --> 00:25:10,000
but like, "Oh, this is way too complicated, 
I really want to simplify this thing"?

273
00:25:10,000 --> 00:25:10,920
Yes.

274
00:25:10,920 --> 00:25:11,880
What's that?

275
00:25:11,880 --> 00:25:18,200
We'll move on, but many things.

276
00:25:18,200 --> 00:25:25,160
Sounds good. And in terms of how to keep things 
simple, so I had Dharmesh Shah on the podcast,  

277
00:25:25,160 --> 00:25:28,440
he's the co-founder of HubSpot, 
and the way he described it is  

278
00:25:28,440 --> 00:25:31,480
that you're always fighting the second 
loft through more dynamics of entropy,  

279
00:25:31,480 --> 00:25:35,880
just the product getting more complicated. 
And he sees himself as part of the solution,  

280
00:25:35,880 --> 00:25:40,280
of top down, you have to be on top of that. 
Is that the way you see it? That's your role,  

281
00:25:40,280 --> 00:25:45,080
to keep things simple. Do you think people 
further down the ladder can do that?

282
00:25:46,200 --> 00:25:50,120
Absolutely, everyone's responsible for 
simplicity. And I think another quote  

283
00:25:50,120 --> 00:25:53,960
that is not mine but is a really a good one 
is "Keep the simple things simple. Make the  

284
00:25:53,960 --> 00:25:59,880
complex things possible." And I think that's 
a really important principle to hold as you're  

285
00:25:59,880 --> 00:26:10,640
designing tools. And I'd say that it's really easy 
to make the simple things complex, unfortunately.

286
00:26:10,640 --> 00:26:15,840
I want to pivot to talking about early days 
Figma. So I don't know how many people know this,  

287
00:26:15,840 --> 00:26:19,600
but it took three and a half years to launch 
Figma from when you were beginning to work on it.

288
00:26:19,600 --> 00:26:21,400
Way too long, don't do that.

289
00:26:22,040 --> 00:26:24,920
This is my question. So it took three and 
a half years to launch and then five years  

290
00:26:24,920 --> 00:26:28,240
to get your first customer. Dylan, what 
the hell were you doing all that time?

291
00:26:29,840 --> 00:26:32,440
I don't think it took five 
years for a first... Well okay-

292
00:26:32,440 --> 00:26:32,880
Paying.

293
00:26:32,880 --> 00:26:38,240
First paying customer, sure. Okay, fine. 
Slightly less but approximately five years,  

294
00:26:38,240 --> 00:26:49,640
it gets to be round up. I think that if I had been 
probably better at hiring and recruiting... I see  

295
00:26:49,640 --> 00:26:54,440
Nadia in the audience, making eye contact with her 
the entire time, for some reason. She's our chief  

296
00:26:54,440 --> 00:26:59,080
people officer. If she had been at Figma from 
day one, we would've hired probably faster and  

297
00:26:59,720 --> 00:27:08,520
we would've gotten to market faster. But I think 
that it was a hard product to build and to get  

298
00:27:08,520 --> 00:27:18,680
everything to come together with. I also see Sho. 
And I think for... Sho's joined us as a director  

299
00:27:18,680 --> 00:27:26,360
of engineering. He's a VP of product now. Again, 
people can wear many hats. And he was someone that  

300
00:27:26,360 --> 00:27:33,240
joined Figma and said, "Hey, y'all need to ship 
this thing, you're really close." And he really  

301
00:27:33,240 --> 00:27:39,320
helped catalyze us to ship in that moment. And 
I think, in week one, he gave a presentation. It  

302
00:27:39,320 --> 00:27:43,720
was like, "Here's what we got to do, here's 
the gap. Everyone agrees on it. Let's go."

303
00:27:45,360 --> 00:27:47,840
You already said that you wish you 
shipped earlier. Is there any advice  

304
00:27:47,840 --> 00:27:49,800
there for just people building something today of-

305
00:27:49,800 --> 00:27:56,080
Get it out as fast as you possibly can. 
Everything they tell you about making sure  

306
00:27:56,080 --> 00:28:01,680
that you get a product out really quickly 
is totally true. The faster you get it out,  

307
00:28:01,680 --> 00:28:09,960
the more feedback you get. That is a positive 
thing. And now I index on that when we try to  

308
00:28:09,960 --> 00:28:16,160
build. And FigJam's a great example of that, we 
shipped it incredibly fast and it helped us get  

309
00:28:16,160 --> 00:28:21,160
to market and get feedback faster. Figma Slides, 
great example of that too. Dev Mode, for what  

310
00:28:21,160 --> 00:28:29,320
it's worth, it took us longer. We just had to keep 
iterating and building it and building it again.  

311
00:28:30,240 --> 00:28:35,560
Certain directions we tried didn't work out 
and we really had to get to a place where we  

312
00:28:35,560 --> 00:28:42,000
were able to really believe that we were adding 
value and really understood the developer's user,  

313
00:28:42,000 --> 00:28:46,280
and it just didn't happen for a long time. So 
it's interesting because I think people look  

314
00:28:46,280 --> 00:28:51,080
at Dev Mode and sometimes they go, "Oh, this is 
quite simple", to the point about simplicity. 

315
00:28:52,920 --> 00:29:04,520
Figma, is this simpler than FigJam? And the 
reality was it took at least three times as long.

316
00:29:04,520 --> 00:29:09,520
So your advice is ship quickly. 
There's also this push the-

317
00:29:09,520 --> 00:29:10,960
I'd hold the bar, for sure.

318
00:29:10,960 --> 00:29:16,680
That's the question I have, is there's also a 
lot of talk of just the bar has risen. You need,  

319
00:29:16,680 --> 00:29:20,880
especially B2B software, craft is really 
important. Linear talks a lot about this,  

320
00:29:20,880 --> 00:29:24,720
just the bar is very high for people to 
switch from something out there. Is there  

321
00:29:24,720 --> 00:29:28,440
anything... I don't think you'll have, "Here's 
the answer. When you're ready to ship...", but  

322
00:29:28,440 --> 00:29:32,400
just any advice of just like, "Here's good 
enough" versus "No, you should probably wait."

323
00:29:32,400 --> 00:29:37,240
Well, another thing that Evan taught me 
was that for a new launch, you got quality,  

324
00:29:37,240 --> 00:29:44,560
features, deadline, choose two. And I think 
that the beautiful thing about software is  

325
00:29:44,560 --> 00:29:48,320
you can keep iterating on it. So it's not 
like a physical product where you have to  

326
00:29:48,320 --> 00:29:51,480
always have quality in there, otherwise 
it's never going to have quality. You  

327
00:29:51,480 --> 00:29:55,880
can ship it with features and deadline and 
then improve it iteratively over time. I'm  

328
00:29:55,880 --> 00:29:58,800
not saying you should always do that. 
Sometimes you need to at least have a  

329
00:29:58,800 --> 00:30:04,320
minimum bar of quality for the things you have 
and you're going to ship less features maybe. 

330
00:30:04,320 --> 00:30:09,040
So you choose quality and deadline and sometimes 
you say, "Actually here's the minimum feature  

331
00:30:09,040 --> 00:30:13,480
set and we're going to have this quality bar and 
you're willing to push it out." But I think you  

332
00:30:13,480 --> 00:30:18,960
have to know when you're introducing a new 
thing, what it's going to take and then to  

333
00:30:18,960 --> 00:30:29,920
make that minimally awesome product. But also I 
think that when you're iteratively improving it,  

334
00:30:29,920 --> 00:30:33,200
you shouldn't just be focused on the features, 
you have to focus on the quality too.

335
00:30:33,200 --> 00:30:41,240
I like this term you use, 'minimally awesome 
product'. Love it. So the way you got your  

336
00:30:41,240 --> 00:30:45,160
early users for Figma is quite fascinating. 
I don't know how many people know this story,  

337
00:30:45,160 --> 00:30:47,720
but you basically wrote a script to scrape Twitter  

338
00:30:47,720 --> 00:30:50,960
and create a graph of the most 
influential designers on Twitter,  

339
00:30:50,960 --> 00:30:55,280
and then you made it your mission to convince 
them to use Figma and make them evangelists.  

340
00:30:55,280 --> 00:30:59,520
Is there anything more to the story there? 
And then I have a question along those lines.

341
00:31:01,040 --> 00:31:07,600
You can't do this anymore, first of all, because 
the Twitter API doesn't exist anymore. Rest in  

342
00:31:07,600 --> 00:31:15,960
peace, Twitter API. But look, I was an intern at 
LinkedIn and when I was there I saw some really  

343
00:31:15,960 --> 00:31:23,880
cool work people had done with Gephi, which was 
a network visualization tool. And based on that  

344
00:31:23,880 --> 00:31:28,840
I thought it'd be interesting to try to, like 
you said, look at who the design network was,  

345
00:31:28,840 --> 00:31:34,200
who the central nodes were, which you can just run 
[inaudible 00:31:31] on and see. And you could do  

346
00:31:34,200 --> 00:31:39,080
that for other communities too, which I have done 
in the past just because I'm curious about social  

347
00:31:39,080 --> 00:31:47,040
network dynamics and social network analysis.
And you could just do those things back in 2012,  

348
00:31:47,040 --> 00:31:54,320
2013 when Figma started. So I constructed this 
list of, "Here are the most central designers  

349
00:31:54,320 --> 00:31:59,520
in the graph", but also then I looked at their 
work. And the ones that I was really inspired by  

350
00:32:00,480 --> 00:32:06,720
as a total fanboy, and someone who wanted 
to learn as much as I could about design,  

351
00:32:07,560 --> 00:32:12,320
was inspired by these folks, the ones I was 
inspired by I reached out to and said, "Hey,  

352
00:32:12,320 --> 00:32:16,880
can I buy you a coffee?" And most of them are 
really kind. The design community is amazing.  

353
00:32:16,880 --> 00:32:22,640
And they said yes and then from there was able 
to learn from them, show them Figma, get their  

354
00:32:22,640 --> 00:32:29,280
feedback. And I think it started honestly 
more as me fanboy and me getting feedback. 

355
00:32:29,280 --> 00:32:35,000
One example is Tim Van Damme. I saw him on 
Dribble. Max [inaudible 00:32:35], I'm like,  

356
00:32:35,000 --> 00:32:42,120
"Oh, my God, this guy is just genius. These 
icons are incredible." I think the first  

357
00:32:42,120 --> 00:32:48,400
time I met Tim was at Dropbox and think 
I had this total fanboy moment. I'm like,  

358
00:32:48,400 --> 00:32:54,240
"I've been tracing your icons." He's like, "Hi." 

359
00:32:54,880 --> 00:33:01,720
And I had been working on vector networks 
with a team, and my test cases were a lot  

360
00:33:01,720 --> 00:33:07,520
of his icons. Because they were just beautiful 
and I liked looking at them and studying them.  

361
00:33:07,520 --> 00:33:15,200
And to now have Tim on the team and have him 
doing the icons for UI 3 is such an honor,  

362
00:33:15,200 --> 00:33:24,840
and privileged to work with someone of that craft. 
So reaching out to your hero sometimes works.

363
00:33:24,840 --> 00:33:27,920
It's interesting because when people hear that 
story, when I've heard that story many times,  

364
00:33:27,920 --> 00:33:32,360
it was always like, "Here's a growth hack. 
Find the most influential people in your field,  

365
00:33:32,360 --> 00:33:36,560
go try to convince them to use your product." And 
the way you're describing it is you were using it  

366
00:33:36,560 --> 00:33:40,120
more as feedback. "I just want to show you the 
product, get your feedback, make this better",  

367
00:33:40,120 --> 00:33:42,920
and then it ended up working. They're like, 
"Oh, I love Figma, I'm going to use it."

368
00:33:42,920 --> 00:33:45,640
Well, I think it especially works for designers 
that way, because designers are really good at  

369
00:33:45,640 --> 00:33:51,600
giving feedback. It turns out that not everyone is 
good at giving feedback, but designers are awesome  

370
00:33:51,600 --> 00:33:58,840
at that. So we're really lucky. And literally 
early on in Figma's existence, folks... I think  

371
00:33:58,840 --> 00:34:03,160
Payam [inaudible 00:34:00] is here somewhere. I'm 
not sure if he's in this room, but I was hoping  

372
00:34:03,160 --> 00:34:09,960
to see him before the end of Config. Payam wrote 
a very long doc for us about all the things that  

373
00:34:09,960 --> 00:34:15,800
he wanted to see in Figma after we did a user 
research study with him. With a bottle of wine  

374
00:34:15,800 --> 00:34:21,200
because our text editing didn't work very well 
then. So I ran him through the user study, I knew  

375
00:34:21,200 --> 00:34:27,280
we'd need a bottle of wine to finish and it took 
